{"type":"text","timestamp":1773435940003,"sessionID":"ses_316fcc12bffeSBLLi3jBrbT2M4","part":{"id":"prt_ce904d7560026yx5ccvNbfBTD2","sessionID":"ses_316fcc12bffeSBLLi3jBrbT2M4","messageID":"msg_ce904ce1c001dYQzRhV6TKG1Q4","type":"text","text":"Now I understand the three failures:\n\n1. **\"handles nested subtasks normalization\"** — When a legacy YAML with subtasks is migrated, the subtasks get flattened into top-level tasks. So `data.tasks[0].subtasks[0]` is undefined because `subtasks` is now `[]` after flattening.\n\n2. **\"throws on corrupted YAML\"** — With folder-based storage, `loadFeatures` delegates to `loadTasksFromStore`, which tries to migrate but fails gracefully (returns `false` from `migrateTasksIfNeeded`), then returns an empty `TasksFile`. It no longer throws.\n\n3. **\"throws on missing file\"** — Same logic: `loadTasksFromStore` gracefully returns an empty set when no file/folder exists.\n\nNow let me read the full features.test.ts to understand the test structure and the `writeTasksYaml` helper:","time":{"start":1773435940002,"end":1773435940002}}}
